{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GtRUW38uWBdgwcooXHB19T","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# OfficeAgent Best Practices\n     2→\n     3→Universal guidelines for all workstreams in the OfficeAgent monorepo.\n     4→\n     5→## Code Organization\n     6→\n     7→### Repo Layout\n     8→- **`agents/<name>/`** -- Each agent is a yarn workspace package\n     9→- **`modules/<name>/`** -- Shared libraries consumed by agents\n    10→- **`.devtools/`** -- CLI, test client, eval browser, and developer scripts\n    11→- **`eval/`** -- Python evaluation framework (separate from the yarn workspace)\n    12→- **`gulp-tasks/`** -- Shared build task definitions (TS and Python variants)\n    13→- **`docker/`** -- Dockerfile, runtime package.json, and container scripts\n    14→\n    15→### Package Naming\n    16→- All packages use the `@officeagent/<name>` scope (e.g., `@officeagent/core`, `@officeagent/create-agent`)\n    17→- Package names in `package.json` must match the directory name under `agents/` or `modules/`\n    18→- Use `workspace:^` for all intra-monorepo dependencies -- never hardcoded versions\n    19→\n    20→### File & Directory Conventions\n    21→- TypeScript source goes in `src/` with output to `dist/src/`\n    22→- Every package declares `\"main\": \"dist/src/index.js\"` and `\"types\": \"dist/src/index.d.ts\"`\n    23→- Python modules use `src/` for source and `tests/` for tests, with a `pyproject.toml` at the package root\n    24→- Prompts live at `agents/<name>/src/prompts/<version>/` (versioned directories)\n    25→\n    26→### Imports\n    27→- Always use scoped imports: `import { ... } from '@officeagent/core'`\n    28→- Never use relative imports across package boundaries (`../../modules/core/...` is wrong)\n    29→- ESLint rule `import/no-relative-packages` enforces this\n    30→- Use `@officeagent/core` for logging, agent base classes, websocket, and utilities\n    31→- Use `@officeagent/message-protocol` for all message type definitions\n    32→\n    33→## Agent Development\n    34→\n    35→### Registry First\n    36→- Every agent must export an `agentRegistry: AgentRegistryConfig` from `src/registry.ts`\n    37→- The registry defines the agent's identity (`id`, `name`, `packageName`, `description`), versions, tools, skills, subagents, and flights\n    38→- Simple agents (e.g., `odsp-agent`, `ppt-creation-agent`) only need metadata -- no versions, flights, or filters required\n    39→- Complex agents (e.g., `create-agent`, `dw-paralegal-agent`) define versioned configurations with model, tools, skills, subagents, and scripts\n    40→\n    41→### Prompt Organization (Versioned Agents)\n    42→- Each version gets its own directory: `src/prompts/<version>/`\n    43→- Standard subdirectories: `skills/`, `subagents/`, `scripts/`, `agent-capabilities/`, `intent-detection/`, `overwrites/`\n    44→- System prompt: `system-prompt.md` (can use EJS templating with `<%- variable %>`)\n    45→- RAI guidelines: `rai.md` (referenced in registry)\n    46→- Each skill has a `SKILL.md` with frontmatter (`name`, `description`) and instructions\n    47→- Each subagent is a standalone `.md` file in the `subagents/` directory\n    48→\n    49→### Skills vs Sub-Agents\n    50→- **Skill**: A set of instructions + scripts the main agent follows directly. Use when the main agent orchestrates the work. Defined in `skills/<name>/SKILL.md`\n    51→- **Sub-agent**: An independent Claude instance with its own system prompt. Use when the task needs isolation, parallel execution, or a focused context window. Defined in `subagents/<name>.md`\n    52→- Decision guide: if the task is a well-scoped step in a pipeline (outline generation, code generation, validation), use a sub-agent. If it is general capability the main agent needs (search, clarification), use a skill\n    53→\n    54→### Flights vs Filters\n    55→- **Flights**: Feature flags that override registry configuration at initialization (version, model, subagents, prompt overwrites, scripts). Key pattern: `OfficeAgent.<AgentName>.<FeatureName>`\n    56→- **Filters**: Runtime rules that dynamically adjust capabilities based on request context. Use for conditional behavior that depends on incoming data, not static feature toggles\n    57→- Use `applicableVersions` on flights to scope overrides to specific versions\n    58→\n    59→### Prompt Versioning\n    60→- Registry `versions[]` array holds versioned configs; `defaultVersion` picks the active one\n    61→- Flights can override the version: `{ flightKey: '...@1.1.0', config: { version: '1.1.0' } }`\n    62→- Prompt overwrites swap individual files: `{ src: 'overwrites/file.md', dst: 'skills/path/file.md' }`\n    63→- When adding new prompt behavior, prefer creating a new version or a flight overwrite rather than mutating existing prompts in place\n    64→\n    65→## Logging\n    66→\n    67→- Use `logInfo`, `logWarn`, `logError`, `logDebug` from `@officeagent/core` -- never use `console.*` in production code (ESLint enforces this)\n    68→- `logInfo`, `logWarn`, `logError` require a numeric tag ID as the first parameter\n    69→- `logDebug` takes a string message directly (no tag ID)\n    70→\n    71→## Testing\n    72→\n    73→### Test Placement\n    74→- TypeScript tests: `<package>/tests/**/*.test.ts` (mirrors source structure)\n    75→- Python tests: `<package>/tests/test_*.py` or `<package>/tests/*_test.py`\n    76→- Mock data goes in `<package>/tests/**/mocks/` (excluded from test discovery)\n    77→- Local-only tests go in `<package>/local-tests/` (excluded from CI)\n    78→\n    79→### Configuration\n    80→- Each TS package has a `jest.config.js` that extends the root config: `const baseConfig = require('../../jest.config.js');`\n    81→- Root `jest.config.js` uses `ts-jest` preset with `testTimeout: 10000`, automatic mock clearing/resetting/restoring\n    82→- Python tests use `pytest.ini` at repo root; coverage only collected in CI (`TF_BUILD` env var)\n    83→- Eval framework has its own `pyproject.toml` with pytest + ruff + black + mypy config\n    84→\n    85→### Running Tests\n    86→- `yarn test` -- run all tests across all workspaces (Jest + pytest via lage)\n    87→- From a specific package directory: `yarn test` runs that package's tests only\n    88→- Python modules: tests run via gulp tasks that invoke `pytest` with the venv Python executable\n    89→- Eval framework: activate venv first, then `pytest eval/tests/`\n    90→\n    91→## Build & Deploy\n    92→\n    93→### Build Pipeline\n    94→- `lage` orchestrates workspace builds respecting dependency order (defined in `lage.config.js`)\n    95→- `build` depends on `^build` (upstream packages build first)\n    96→- Each package's `gulp build` task: clean -> copy files -> compile TS (if tsconfig.json exists) -> dependency check\n    97→- Python modules: `gulp build` installs in editable mode, validates syntax\n    98→- Full build: `yarn build` = lage build + Docker image build + debug link setup\n    99→\n   100→### Key Commands\n   101→- `yarn build` -- full build (requires Docker Desktop running)\n   102→- `yarn compile` -- lage build only (no Docker)\n   103→- `yarn reload` -- hot reload: build changes and copy to running container\n   104→- `yarn start` -- start Docker container + test client\n   105→- `yarn start:compose` -- start via Docker Compose (supports scaling)\n   106→- `yarn stop` -- stop Docker container\n   107→- `oagent ping` -- health check the running container\n   108→- `oagent gen \"prompt\" -o ./file.docx` -- generate a document via CLI\n   109→\n   110→### Docker\n   111→- The Docker image is built from `docker/Dockerfile` using the repo root as build context\n   112→- Modules are copied into the container via `docker/copy-modules.js`; Python modules installed in editable mode via `docker/install-py-modules.js`\n   113→- Runtime Node.js dependencies are in `docker/package.json` (managed with `npm`, separate from yarn workspaces)\n   114→- Container exposes ports: 6010 (API), 6011 (internal), 6020 (debug)\n   115→- Use `yarn reload` for iterative development -- only use `yarn build` when Dockerfile, container dependencies, or infrastructure files change\n   116→\n   117→### Adding a New Package\n   118→1. Create directory under `agents/` or `modules/` with `package.json` using `@officeagent/<name>` scope\n   119→2. Add `gulpfile.mjs` that re-exports from `../../gulp-tasks/default-tasks.mjs` (TS) or uses `default-tasks-py.mjs` (Python)\n   120→3. Add `jest.config.js` extending root config (TS) or ensure `tests/` directory follows pytest patterns (Python)\n   121→4. Add `tsconfig.json` extending root config (TS only)\n   122→5. Run `yarn install` to register the new workspace\n   123→\n   124→## Code Style\n   125→\n   126→- TypeScript: single quotes, semicolons required (ESLint enforced)\n   127→- Unused variables must be prefixed with `_` (e.g., `_unusedParam`)\n   128→- Python (eval framework): black for formatting (line-length 100), ruff for linting, mypy for type checking\n   129→- ESLint config is flat format (`eslint.config.mjs`) -- no `.eslintrc` files\n   130→\n   131→## Common Pitfalls\n   132→\n   133→- **PowerShell required**: `yarn` and `oagent` commands must run in PowerShell, not Command Prompt or bash on Windows\n   134→- **Docker Desktop must be running** before `yarn build` -- the build step includes Docker image creation and will fail without it\n   135→- **Python venv activation**: for terminal Python work (pytest, pip, eval scripts), activate with `.\\venv\\Scripts\\Activate.ps1` (Windows) or `source venv/bin/activate` (Linux/Mac). VS Code auto-detects `./venv`\n   136→- **Environment variables**: CLI config uses `OAGENT_` prefix (see `.env.example`); container config uses `OfficePy__` prefix for OfficePy settings\n   137→- **No `console.*` in production TS**: use `@officeagent/core` logging functions; ESLint blocks console usage outside test files\n   138→- **Workspace dependency format**: always use `\"workspace:^\"` in package.json, never pin versions for monorepo packages\n   139→- **Build order matters**: if you change a module, downstream agents need rebuilding -- `lage` handles this automatically with `yarn build`, but manual `tsc` in one package may miss dependents\n   140→- **Node.js >= 22 required**: defined in root `package.json` engines; the container uses its own Node binary from `docker/package.json`\n   141→- **Yarn 4.10.3**: the repo uses Yarn Berry (v4) -- do not use Yarn Classic (v1) commands or flags\n   142→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"059c34c4-4758-4e2f-87ba-9357713e7c91","uuid":"e9e9fb79-57eb-4591-a742-e04c4b0bbc29","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\Users\\yemishin\\OfficeAgent\\docs\\BEST_PRACTICES.md","content":"# OfficeAgent Best Practices\n\nUniversal guidelines for all workstreams in the OfficeAgent monorepo.\n\n## Code Organization\n\n### Repo Layout\n- **`agents/<name>/`** -- Each agent is a yarn workspace package\n- **`modules/<name>/`** -- Shared libraries consumed by agents\n- **`.devtools/`** -- CLI, test client, eval browser, and developer scripts\n- **`eval/`** -- Python evaluation framework (separate from the yarn workspace)\n- **`gulp-tasks/`** -- Shared build task definitions (TS and Python variants)\n- **`docker/`** -- Dockerfile, runtime package.json, and container scripts\n\n### Package Naming\n- All packages use the `@officeagent/<name>` scope (e.g., `@officeagent/core`, `@officeagent/create-agent`)\n- Package names in `package.json` must match the directory name under `agents/` or `modules/`\n- Use `workspace:^` for all intra-monorepo dependencies -- never hardcoded versions\n\n### File & Directory Conventions\n- TypeScript source goes in `src/` with output to `dist/src/`\n- Every package declares `\"main\": \"dist/src/index.js\"` and `\"types\": \"dist/src/index.d.ts\"`\n- Python modules use `src/` for source and `tests/` for tests, with a `pyproject.toml` at the package root\n- Prompts live at `agents/<name>/src/prompts/<version>/` (versioned directories)\n\n### Imports\n- Always use scoped imports: `import { ... } from '@officeagent/core'`\n- Never use relative imports across package boundaries (`../../modules/core/...` is wrong)\n- ESLint rule `import/no-relative-packages` enforces this\n- Use `@officeagent/core` for logging, agent base classes, websocket, and utilities\n- Use `@officeagent/message-protocol` for all message type definitions\n\n## Agent Development\n\n### Registry First\n- Every agent must export an `agentRegistry: AgentRegistryConfig` from `src/registry.ts`\n- The registry defines the agent's identity (`id`, `name`, `packageName`, `description`), versions, tools, skills, subagents, and flights\n- Simple agents (e.g., `odsp-agent`, `ppt-creation-agent`) only need metadata -- no versions, flights, or filters required\n- Complex agents (e.g., `create-agent`, `dw-paralegal-agent`) define versioned configurations with model, tools, skills, subagents, and scripts\n\n### Prompt Organization (Versioned Agents)\n- Each version gets its own directory: `src/prompts/<version>/`\n- Standard subdirectories: `skills/`, `subagents/`, `scripts/`, `agent-capabilities/`, `intent-detection/`, `overwrites/`\n- System prompt: `system-prompt.md` (can use EJS templating with `<%- variable %>`)\n- RAI guidelines: `rai.md` (referenced in registry)\n- Each skill has a `SKILL.md` with frontmatter (`name`, `description`) and instructions\n- Each subagent is a standalone `.md` file in the `subagents/` directory\n\n### Skills vs Sub-Agents\n- **Skill**: A set of instructions + scripts the main agent follows directly. Use when the main agent orchestrates the work. Defined in `skills/<name>/SKILL.md`\n- **Sub-agent**: An independent Claude instance with its own system prompt. Use when the task needs isolation, parallel execution, or a focused context window. Defined in `subagents/<name>.md`\n- Decision guide: if the task is a well-scoped step in a pipeline (outline generation, code generation, validation), use a sub-agent. If it is general capability the main agent needs (search, clarification), use a skill\n\n### Flights vs Filters\n- **Flights**: Feature flags that override registry configuration at initialization (version, model, subagents, prompt overwrites, scripts). Key pattern: `OfficeAgent.<AgentName>.<FeatureName>`\n- **Filters**: Runtime rules that dynamically adjust capabilities based on request context. Use for conditional behavior that depends on incoming data, not static feature toggles\n- Use `applicableVersions` on flights to scope overrides to specific versions\n\n### Prompt Versioning\n- Registry `versions[]` array holds versioned configs; `defaultVersion` picks the active one\n- Flights can override the version: `{ flightKey: '...@1.1.0', config: { version: '1.1.0' } }`\n- Prompt overwrites swap individual files: `{ src: 'overwrites/file.md', dst: 'skills/path/file.md' }`\n- When adding new prompt behavior, prefer creating a new version or a flight overwrite rather than mutating existing prompts in place\n\n## Logging\n\n- Use `logInfo`, `logWarn`, `logError`, `logDebug` from `@officeagent/core` -- never use `console.*` in production code (ESLint enforces this)\n- `logInfo`, `logWarn`, `logError` require a numeric tag ID as the first parameter\n- `logDebug` takes a string message directly (no tag ID)\n\n## Testing\n\n### Test Placement\n- TypeScript tests: `<package>/tests/**/*.test.ts` (mirrors source structure)\n- Python tests: `<package>/tests/test_*.py` or `<package>/tests/*_test.py`\n- Mock data goes in `<package>/tests/**/mocks/` (excluded from test discovery)\n- Local-only tests go in `<package>/local-tests/` (excluded from CI)\n\n### Configuration\n- Each TS package has a `jest.config.js` that extends the root config: `const baseConfig = require('../../jest.config.js');`\n- Root `jest.config.js` uses `ts-jest` preset with `testTimeout: 10000`, automatic mock clearing/resetting/restoring\n- Python tests use `pytest.ini` at repo root; coverage only collected in CI (`TF_BUILD` env var)\n- Eval framework has its own `pyproject.toml` with pytest + ruff + black + mypy config\n\n### Running Tests\n- `yarn test` -- run all tests across all workspaces (Jest + pytest via lage)\n- From a specific package directory: `yarn test` runs that package's tests only\n- Python modules: tests run via gulp tasks that invoke `pytest` with the venv Python executable\n- Eval framework: activate venv first, then `pytest eval/tests/`\n\n## Build & Deploy\n\n### Build Pipeline\n- `lage` orchestrates workspace builds respecting dependency order (defined in `lage.config.js`)\n- `build` depends on `^build` (upstream packages build first)\n- Each package's `gulp build` task: clean -> copy files -> compile TS (if tsconfig.json exists) -> dependency check\n- Python modules: `gulp build` installs in editable mode, validates syntax\n- Full build: `yarn build` = lage build + Docker image build + debug link setup\n\n### Key Commands\n- `yarn build` -- full build (requires Docker Desktop running)\n- `yarn compile` -- lage build only (no Docker)\n- `yarn reload` -- hot reload: build changes and copy to running container\n- `yarn start` -- start Docker container + test client\n- `yarn start:compose` -- start via Docker Compose (supports scaling)\n- `yarn stop` -- stop Docker container\n- `oagent ping` -- health check the running container\n- `oagent gen \"prompt\" -o ./file.docx` -- generate a document via CLI\n\n### Docker\n- The Docker image is built from `docker/Dockerfile` using the repo root as build context\n- Modules are copied into the container via `docker/copy-modules.js`; Python modules installed in editable mode via `docker/install-py-modules.js`\n- Runtime Node.js dependencies are in `docker/package.json` (managed with `npm`, separate from yarn workspaces)\n- Container exposes ports: 6010 (API), 6011 (internal), 6020 (debug)\n- Use `yarn reload` for iterative development -- only use `yarn build` when Dockerfile, container dependencies, or infrastructure files change\n\n### Adding a New Package\n1. Create directory under `agents/` or `modules/` with `package.json` using `@officeagent/<name>` scope\n2. Add `gulpfile.mjs` that re-exports from `../../gulp-tasks/default-tasks.mjs` (TS) or uses `default-tasks-py.mjs` (Python)\n3. Add `jest.config.js` extending root config (TS) or ensure `tests/` directory follows pytest patterns (Python)\n4. Add `tsconfig.json` extending root config (TS only)\n5. Run `yarn install` to register the new workspace\n\n## Code Style\n\n- TypeScript: single quotes, semicolons required (ESLint enforced)\n- Unused variables must be prefixed with `_` (e.g., `_unusedParam`)\n- Python (eval framework): black for formatting (line-length 100), ruff for linting, mypy for type checking\n- ESLint config is flat format (`eslint.config.mjs`) -- no `.eslintrc` files\n\n## Common Pitfalls\n\n- **PowerShell required**: `yarn` and `oagent` commands must run in PowerShell, not Command Prompt or bash on Windows\n- **Docker Desktop must be running** before `yarn build` -- the build step includes Docker image creation and will fail without it\n- **Python venv activation**: for terminal Python work (pytest, pip, eval scripts), activate with `.\\venv\\Scripts\\Activate.ps1` (Windows) or `source venv/bin/activate` (Linux/Mac). VS Code auto-detects `./venv`\n- **Environment variables**: CLI config uses `OAGENT_` prefix (see `.env.example`); container config uses `OfficePy__` prefix for OfficePy settings\n- **No `console.*` in production TS**: use `@officeagent/core` logging functions; ESLint blocks console usage outside test files\n- **Workspace dependency format**: always use `\"workspace:^\"` in package.json, never pin versions for monorepo packages\n- **Build order matters**: if you change a module, downstream agents need rebuilding -- `lage` handles this automatically with `yarn build`, but manual `tsc` in one package may miss dependents\n- **Node.js >= 22 required**: defined in root `package.json` engines; the container uses its own Node binary from `docker/package.json`\n- **Yarn 4.10.3**: the repo uses Yarn Berry (v4) -- do not use Yarn Classic (v1) commands or flags\n","numLines":142,"startLine":1,"totalLines":142}}}
