gents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/conversion/jsonToHTML/security\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/conversion/jsonToHTML/themes\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/core\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/hooks\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/plugins\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/prompts\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/reference\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/scripts\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/skills\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/themes\n/c/Users/yemishin/OfficeAgent/agents/create-agent/src/prompts/1.0.0/skills/docx/validation","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01VcS2pjCQDmBrQu85ZKAMvr","session_id":"059c34c4-4758-4e2f-87ba-9357713e7c91","uuid":"1f048307-14a1-4938-8608-b227783b81a5"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HqqrwAeaQWrSsi5vgqmE4N","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: analyze-pr\n     3→description: Analyze an Azure DevOps pull request from a URL with full code diffs. Fetches PR metadata, commit history, file-by-file diffs, and provides comprehensive context for dependent changes. Use when user pastes a PR link, says \"analyze PR\", \"what changed in this PR\", \"PR diff\", \"review this PR\", or provides an office.visualstudio.com or dev.azure.com PR URL.\n     4→allowed-tools: Bash, Read, Write, Grep, Glob\n     5→metadata:\n     6→  author: Snehal Gupta\n     7→  version: 1.0.0\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→# Analyze Pull Request\n    11→\n    12→You are a helpful assistant that produces **clear, engineer-friendly PR analysis reports**. Given a PR link, you fetch the full context (metadata, commits, file-by-file diffs) and write a report that any engineer can read top-to-bottom to understand *what changed, why, and how it affects them*. Use ASCII diagrams for flows, plain language for explanations, and keep raw diffs as a reference appendix. The report is always saved to a `.md` file.\n    13→\n    14→## Usage\n    15→\n    16→**Basic:** `/analyze-pr <PR_URL>`\n    17→**Specific iteration:** `/analyze-pr <PR_URL> --commit <commit_id>`\n    18→**Examples:**\n    19→- `/analyze-pr https://office.visualstudio.com/ISS/_git/augloop-workflows/pullrequest/4877210`\n    20→- `/analyze-pr https://office.visualstudio.com/Office/_git/1JS/pullrequest/12345 --commit abc123def`\n    21→- \"Analyze this PR: https://office.visualstudio.com/...\"\n    22→\n    23→---\n    24→\n    25→## Step 1: Run the Comprehensive Fetch Script\n    26→\n    27→Use the Python script that fetches **full code diffs** for every file in the PR:\n    28→\n    29→```bash\n    30→python3 \"<SKILL_BASE_DIR>/fetch-pr-changes.py\" \"<PR_URL>\"\n    31→```\n    32→\n    33→Where `<SKILL_BASE_DIR>` is the base directory for this skill (shown at the top of the skill prompt).\n    34→\n    35→To analyze a specific commit/iteration instead of the latest:\n    36→```bash\n    37→python3 \"<SKILL_BASE_DIR>/fetch-pr-changes.py\" \"<PR_URL>\" --commit <commit_id>\n    38→```\n    39→\n    40→### What the script fetches:\n    41→1. **PR Metadata** — title, author, status, draft flag, branches, creation date\n    42→2. **PR Description** — full description text from the PR\n    43→3. **Commit History** — all commits in the PR with author, date, and message\n    44→4. **Iteration Info** — base commit (merge base) and head commit for diffing\n    45→5. **File List** — all changed files categorized as Added/Edited/Deleted/Renamed\n    46→6. **Full Code Diffs** — unified diff for every changed file, fetched in parallel\n    47→   - For **added** files: full new file content shown in a code block\n    48→   - For **edited** files: unified diff with context lines showing exactly what changed\n    49→   - For **deleted** files: unified diff showing removed content\n    50→   - For **renamed** files: diff between old and new paths/content\n    51→7. **Directory Summary** — files grouped by directory for quick orientation\n    52→\n    53→### Iteration / Commit Selection:\n    54→- **Default behavior:** Always uses the **latest iteration** (latest push to the PR)\n    55→- **`--commit` flag:** If the user specifies a commit ID, the script finds the iteration containing that commit and diffs against that iteration's base\n    56→- Each iteration represents a push to the PR branch. The diff is between the iteration's `commonRefCommit` (merge base with target) and `sourceRefCommit` (PR head at that push)\n    57→\n    58→**Authentication** (checked in order):\n    59→1. **Codespace `ado-auth-helper`** — automatic in GitHub Codespaces\n    60→2. **Environment variable** — `AZURE_DEVOPS_EXT_PAT` or `MS_ADO_PAT`\n    61→3. **az CLI** — `az account get-access-token` (works on local machines after `az login`)\n    62→\n    63→---\n    64→\n    65→## Step 2: Read and Comprehend the Output\n    66→\n    67→After the script runs, **read the full output carefully** and build a comprehensive understanding:\n    68→\n    69→### 2a. Understand the PR intent\n    70→- Read the PR title, description, and commit messages\n    71→- Identify the core purpose: new feature, bug fix, refactor, config change, etc.\n    72→\n    73→### 2b. Analyze each file's changes\n    74→For each file in the diff output:\n    75→- **What was changed** — specific lines added, removed, or modified\n    76→- **Why it was changed** — infer from context, variable names, comments, PR description\n    77→- **Impact on public APIs** — new interfaces, types, exports, function signatures\n    78→- **Impact on configuration** — new settings, feature flags, manifest entries\n    79→\n    80→### 2c. Identify cross-cutting concerns\n    81→- New types/interfaces that other packages might need to import\n    82→- New exports added to barrel files (index.ts)\n    83→- New enum values or configuration keys\n    84→- Changes to workflow manifests, signal types, or annotation types\n    85→- New feature flags / ChangeGates\n    86→\n    87→---\n    88→\n    89→## Step 3: Write the Analysis Report\n    90→\n    91→Write the analysis as a **clear, engineer-friendly report** that someone can read top-to-bottom and fully understand the PR without looking at the code. The report is both displayed to the user AND saved to a file.\n    92→\n    93→### Writing style rules:\n    94→- **Write for a senior engineer** who hasn't seen this code before — assume zero context\n    95→- **Lead with \"why\"** before \"what\" — explain the purpose before listing changes\n    96→- **Use plain language** — avoid jargon dumps; explain concepts inline\n    97→- **Use ASCII diagrams** to show data flows, architecture, and request/response paths\n    98→- **Group by concept**, not by file — readers care about *what the PR does*, not which file it's in\n    99→- **Show key code snippets inline** — the important type definitions, function signatures, and enum values that another engineer would need\n   100→- **Keep the raw diffs** at the bottom for reference — they're valuable but shouldn't be the first thing someone reads\n   101→\n   102→### Report template:\n   103→\n   104→```markdown\n   105→# PR Analysis: {title}\n   106→\n   107→> **PR:** [{prId}]({PR_URL})\n   108→> **Author:** {author} | **Status:** {status} | **Created:** {date}\n   109→> **Branch:** `{source}` → `{target}`\n   110→\n   111→---\n   112→\n   113→## TL;DR\n   114→\n   115→{2-3 sentence plain-English summary of what this PR does and why it matters.\n   116→Write this so a PM or a new team member could understand it.\n   117→Example: \"This PR adds the ability for Office Agent to create SharePoint sites,\n   118→Teams channels, and Loop workspaces on behalf of the user. It reuses the\n   119→existing WebSocket infrastructure and is gated behind a feature flag\n   120→that's off in production.\"}\n   121→\n   122→---\n   123→\n   124→## What Changed (at a glance)\n   125→\n   126→| | Files | What |\n   127→|---|---|---|\n   128→| **Added** | {N} | {one-line summary, e.g. \"new handler, tests, design doc\"} |\n   129→| **Edited** | {N} | {one-line summary, e.g. \"types, routing, config, workflow manifest\"} |\n   130→| **Deleted** | {N} | {one-line summary or \"—\"} |\n   131→\n   132→---\n   133→\n   134→## How It Works\n   135→\n   136→{Explain the end-to-end flow using an ASCII diagram.\n   137→Show how a request enters the system, gets routed, processed, and returns a response.\n   138→This is the MOST IMPORTANT section — make it crystal clear.}\n   139→\n   140→**Example diagram style:**\n   141→\n   142→```\n   143→  Client                    AugLoop Workflow              OfficePy Container\n   144→    │                            │                              │\n   145→    │  CreateWorkspaceSignal     │                              │\n   146→    │ ─────────────────────────> │                              │\n   147→    │                            │  workspace_request (WS)      │\n   148→    │                            │ ───────────────────────────> │\n   149→    │                            │                              │  create workspace\n   150→    │                            │  workspace_response (WS)     │  via Graph API\n   151→    │                            │ <─────────────────────────── │\n   152→    │  CreateWorkspaceResult     │                              │\n   153→    │ <───────────────────────── │                              │\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→{After the diagram, walk through each numbered step in plain English:\n   157→1. Client sends a `CreateWorkspaceSignal` with requestType `'create-workspace'`\n   158→2. The workflow routes it to `OfficeAgentHandler`, which checks the feature flag\n   159→3. If enabled, `CreateWorkspaceHandler` opens a WebSocket to OfficePy...\n   160→etc.}\n   161→\n   162→---\n   163→\n   164→## Detailed Changes\n   165→\n   166→{Group changes by CONCEPT, not by file. Use sub-sections like:}\n   167→\n   168→### 1. New Types & Data Model\n   169→\n   170→{Explain what new types were introduced and what they represent.\n   171→Show the key interfaces as code blocks. Explain the design choices\n   172→(e.g., \"uses a discriminated union pattern for extensibility\").}\n   173→\n   174→```typescript\n   175→// Key new types (from types/office-agent/src/tiles.ts)\n   176→interface ICreateWorkspaceSignal {\n   177→  userMessage: string;\n   178→  requestType: 'create-workspace';\n   179→  workspaceName?: string;\n   180→  workspaceType?: WorkspaceType;\n   181→  contextEntities?: IContextEntity[];\n   182→  // ...\n   183→}\n   184→```\n   185→\n   186→### 2. Core Logic\n   187→\n   188→{Explain the main handler/service/business logic.\n   189→Focus on: what does it do, how does error handling work,\n   190→what are the important timeouts/retries.\n   191→Show key method signatures.}\n   192→\n   193→### 3. Wiring & Integration\n   194→\n   195→{How is the new feature connected to the existing system?\n   196→New switch cases, new imports, workflow manifest changes, etc.\n   197→A small before/after is helpful:}\n   198→\n   199→```\n   200→BEFORE:  switch(requestType) → InputMessage | WarmUp | ConversationIdUpdate\n   201→AFTER:   switch(requestType) → InputMessage | WarmUp | ConversationIdUpdate | CreateWorkspace ← NEW\n   202→```\n   203→\n   204→### 4. Configuration & Feature Flags\n   205→\n   206→{List every new setting, ChangeGate, or config change.\n   207→Use a table for clarity:}\n   208→\n   209→| Flag / Config | Value | Where |\n   210→|---|---|---|\n   211→| `EnableCreateWorkspaceIntent` | `true` in dev/test/int, `false` in prod | settings.json |\n   212→\n   213→### 5. Testing\n   214→\n   215→{What tests were added? What do they cover?\n   216→List the key test scenarios as bullet points.}\n   217→\n   218→---\n   219→\n   220→## For Dependent Repos\n   221→\n   222→{This section is specifically for engineers in OTHER repos who need to\n   223→integrate with or react to these changes.}\n   224→\n   225→### New API Surface\n   226→\n   227→{List every new public type, enum, class, and export that is now available.\n   228→Use a table with import paths:}\n   229→\n   230→| What | Import from | Type name / Value |\n   231→|---|---|---|\n   232→| `ICreateWorkspaceSignal` | `@augloop-types/office-agent` | Signal interface |\n   233→| `CreateWorkspaceSignal` | `@augloop-types/office-agent` | `AugLoop_OfficeAgent_CreateWorkspaceSignal` |\n   234→| ... | ... | ... |\n   235→\n   236→### What You Need to Do\n   237→\n   238→{Actionable checklist for dependent repos:}\n   239→\n   240→- [ ] Handle new signal type `AugLoop_OfficeAgent_CreateWorkspaceSignal` if you process office-agent signals\n   241→- [ ] Handle new annotation type `AugLoop_OfficeAgent_CreateWorkspaceResult` if you consume office-agent results\n   242→- [ ] Enable feature flag `@augloop-utils/office-agent.EnableCreateWorkspaceIntent:true` in your flights\n   243→- [ ] ...\n   244→\n   245→### Breaking Changes\n   246→\n   247→{Explicit \"yes there are breaking changes\" or \"no breaking changes\".\n   248→If yes, explain exactly what breaks and how to fix it.}\n   249→\n   250→---\n   251→\n   252→## File-by-File Reference\n   253→\n   254→{Collapsible or flat list of every file with its change type and a\n   255→ONE-LINE description of what changed in that file:}\n   256→\n   257→| File | Change | Summary |\n   258→|---|---|---|\n   259→| `types/office-agent/src/tiles.ts` | edit | Add `RequestType.CreateWorkspace`, new signal + entity interfaces |\n   260→| `utils/office-agent/src/service/create-workspace-handler.ts` | add | 586-line handler with WebSocket integration |\n   261→| ... | ... | ... |\n   262→\n   263→---\n   264→\n   265→## Raw Diff Output\n   266→\n   267→<details>\n   268→<summary>Click to expand full unified diffs for all {N} files</summary>\n   269→\n   270→{Paste the raw script output here — the full unified diffs.\n   271→This is the reference material. Engineers who need exact line changes can find them here.}\n   272→\n   273→</details>\n   274→```\n   275→\n   276→---\n   277→\n   278→## Step 4: Save Analysis to File\n   279→\n   280→**IMPORTANT:** Always save the full analysis report to a markdown file.\n   281→\n   282→### Steps:\n   283→1. Create the output directory if it doesn't exist:\n   284→   ```bash\n   285→   mkdir -p \"<SKILL_BASE_DIR>/output\"\n   286→   ```\n   287→\n   288→2. Use the **Write** tool to save the complete report (the markdown from Step 3) to:\n   289→   ```\n   290→   <SKILL_BASE_DIR>/output/pr-{prId}-analysis.md\n   291→   ```\n   292→\n   293→3. **Always tell the user the full path** at the end of your response:\n   294→   ```\n   295→   Analysis saved to: <SKILL_BASE_DIR>/output/pr-{prId}-analysis.md\n   296→   ```\n   297→\n   298→The saved file is a **portable, self-contained artifact** — another engineer can read it end-to-end and fully understand the PR without access to the original repo.\n   299→\n   300→---\n   301→\n   302→## Error Handling\n   303→\n   304→### Script Fails\n   305→If the Python script fails, check:\n   306→- Is `az` CLI available? (`which az` / `where az`)\n   307→- Has the user run `az login`? (local machine auth)\n   308→- Is `~/ado-auth-helper` present? (Codespace auth)\n   309→- Is `MS_ADO_PAT` or `AZURE_DEVOPS_EXT_PAT` set? (PAT-based auth)\n   310→- Does the user have access to the target ADO project?\n   311→\n   312→### Authentication Issues\n   313→- **In Codespaces:** The `ado-auth-helper` handles auth automatically. If it fails, ask the user to reload the VS Code window.\n   314→- **On local machines:** The script uses `az account get-access-token` (requires `az login` first). Alternatively, set `AZURE_DEVOPS_EXT_PAT` or `MS_ADO_PAT` env var with a valid PAT.\n   315→\n   316→### Large PRs\n   317→The script fetches diffs in parallel (8 threads). For very large PRs (50+ files), the output may be extensive. Focus your analysis on:\n   318→1. Non-generated files first (skip `.g.ts`, auto-generated code)\n   319→2. Public API surface changes (types, interfaces, exports)\n   320→3. Handler/logic changes over configuration/manifest changes\n   321→\n   322→---\n   323→\n   324→## Examples\n   325→\n   326→### Example 1: Cross-repo PR with full context\n   327→```\n   328→User: \"/analyze-pr https://office.visualstudio.com/ISS/_git/augloop-workflows/pullrequest/4877210\"\n   329→Assistant:\n   330→1. Runs fetch-pr-changes.py -> gets 111KB of diffs across 15 files\n   331→2. Reads all diffs, understands the PR adds a \"Create Workspace\" intent\n   332→3. Identifies key new types: ICreateWorkspaceSignal, ICreateWorkspaceResult, CreateWorkspaceHandler\n   333→4. Notes new ChangeGate: EnableCreateWorkspaceIntent\n   334→5. Presents structured analysis with types, handler logic, config changes\n   335→6. Highlights impact: new signal/annotation types, new exports, new feature flag\n   336→7. Saves to: .claude/skills/analyze-pr/output/pr-4877210-analysis.md\n   337→8. Tells user: \"Analysis saved to: /workspaces/1JS/midgard/.claude/skills/analyze-pr/output/pr-4877210-analysis.md\"\n   338→```\n   339→\n   340→### Example 2: Specific commit analysis\n   341→```\n   342→User: \"/analyze-pr https://office.visualstudio.com/Office/_git/1JS/pullrequest/98765 --commit abc123\"\n   343→Assistant:\n   344→1. Runs fetch-pr-changes.py with --commit abc123\n   345→2. Finds the iteration containing that commit\n   346→3. Diffs against that iteration's base (not the latest)\n   347→4. Presents analysis scoped to that specific push\n   348→5. Saves to: .claude/skills/analyze-pr/output/pr-98765-analysis.md\n   349→```\n   350→\n   351→### Example 3: Dependent repo context\n   352→```\n   353→User: \"I need to make changes in my repo based on this PR. Analyze it for me:\n   354→       https://office.visualstudio.com/ISS/_git/augloop-workflows/pullrequest/4877210\"\n   355→Assistant:\n   356→1. Runs full analysis\n   357→2. Emphasizes public API surface: new types, interfaces, exports\n   358→3. Lists exact import paths and type signatures\n   359→4. Notes configuration requirements (feature flags, manifest entries)\n   360→5. Provides actionable guidance for the dependent repo\n   361→6. Saves to: .claude/skills/analyze-pr/output/pr-4877210-analysis.md\n   362→```\n   363→\n   364→---\n   365→\n   366→## References\n   367→\n   368→- [ADO REST API - PR Iterations](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/azure-devops/git/pull-request-iterations)\n   369→- [ADO REST API - PR Iteration Changes](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/azure-devops/git/pull-request-iteration-changes)\n   370→- [ADO REST API - Items (file content)](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/azure-devops/git/items/get)\n   371→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JgzknBttobEMZ4qK1jH68n","session_id":"059c34c4-4758-4e2f-87ba-9357713e7c91","uuid":"7940e796-851f-4693-be82-d4b1a8c757d1"}
